I mean, I was just looking at the polls today and it's pretty clear. All the polls indicate that majority blame the president for what's going on. And people don't like the idea of shutdown, don't think it's a good idea to shut down the government as a leverage point over building the wall that we know Mexico was going to pay for. And, you know, to me, they think, you know, we should get a deal. We should be able to reach a deal. So, you know, to Dana's sister's point, it'd be nice if people sat down and really thought about this and really -- were able to negotiate.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Do you think, Juan --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But no, let me finish. But here you have a situation where you had Republicans and Democrats make a deal. McConnell said here's a deal. It was the president who shutdown the government. So now you have Vice President Pence, Jared Kushner meeting with Mitch McConnell, they're trying to figure out some way to help the president save face because that's all this is about. And when he does something -- and I think that Pelosi was very clear. And I think the State Department, you know, when they had to say, you know, you can't go, it's very clear. He did talk about the commercial itinerary in a way that would have endangered her life and the life of everyone on there. But guess what? In the conservative media bubble, you get the kind of playground tit for tat -- oh, Adam Schiff was on, remember Adam Schiff, the one that the president misspelled his name with the Ts -- It's unbelievable that we are at this juvenile level. But I think the American people from the poll say enough of this playground behavior. It's not good. It's not good governance and it's not who we are.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, to that, Juan --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It is who we are.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- Nancy started it. How's that --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, here we go.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Dr. Nicole Saphier, Juan says right now the polls indicate that everybody blames the president for the shutdown. If the president were to cut a deal, get the wall, and reopen the government, would the American people give him credit for ending the shutdown and his base would be very ecstatic about the wall funding?

utterances.speaker: NICOLE SAPHIER, HOST
utterances.utterance: Yes. Well, of course, his base would be very happy. But I'm sure that the other side, who never supports him, would come up with something else. And he would not get credit for that because --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: But there's more of an upside for the president here.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: Right. I do agree. I think that they really need to hone in -- you know, he has compromised -- he's compromised on the cost of the border wall. He's gone from $21 billion down to $5.7 billion. He compromised on DACA. I mean, these are things that happened with his campaign, you know. He's doing what he said in his campaign. He lowered corporate tax. He bombed ISIS. He's bringing the troops home. He has to do the wall. He has to do something here. If he foregoes the wall, he's going to lose his base and the Republicans are really going to suffer from this. And now this tit for tat -- and it really is nanny, nanny, bobo, but it's on both side. And it's just is. I mean, Pelosi is in Hawaii. She comes back and she says she's going to pull the reins on this too, which, OK, and then he cancels her trip. I mean, it is a back and forth. I want to see back in the White House, get some of their cronies, get in the Oval Office, lock themselves in, and hash out a deal. Like there's no -- OK, let's shake hands and let's move on with the day. No, you stay in that office until you figure it out because you have 800,000 people not getting paid. And when you're praising the unemployment rate how it keeps going down, but now all of sudden we have employed individuals not getting paid. They're making GoFundMe accounts. They're having to file for unemployment. This isn't right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, doc (ph), you know, I just want to point out that you just said this is all about the president wanting to make a political point. It's not about border security --

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: This is what he got elected to do --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: This is all he wants --

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: -- by the American people, whether you agree with it or not. He got elected saying he was doing a wall.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, oh, no, no. He got -- you're wrong. He got elected saying Mexico would pay for this wall. No, we're not near that. And so, you have him --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: A lot of people believed though the new NAFTA deal gets Mexico to pay for it. But, Juan --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, get out of here. No, let me finish this point. This is important. You have now Gary Cohn, the president's economic advisor --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It was friction free --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. So, let me talk --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We always cut him off.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You have the Federal Reserve Bank chair here in New York saying what's going on right now? It's slowing U.S. economic growth. The president lets Mrs. Trump fly last night. He won't let Pelosi fly.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan, he is not negotiating.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, my God. I thought the principle was in the letter --

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: -- in the Oval Office. We don't need her. She can go.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, we don't need her. But the principle on the letter was --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. Let's get everybody else --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It would be interesting to see an actual specific plan by the Democrats that -- because now, we have them on record saying they're for enhanced border security. They actually say now. You would know their leaders said it was immoral, remember? Walls were immoral. And now you have them backtracking and say, wait a minute -- would we really need to see a plan, a plan that actually shows a border without a wall. I would like to see that because the thing is, if you want a deal you're going to have to create money for an enhanced border, right? That's what it would be. So, the Democrats have to come up with a specific deal, right, with this money that doesn't have any wall. I would like to see that. Do you think that's possible?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Juan, do you believe that? You could do it without a wall? Then you should write it down right now. I want to see you draw it out.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't think this is so hard.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's impossible.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Jesse was making fun of me yesterday for going through the steps, you know, the added funding in terms of security personnel, the drone --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But no wall.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Because it's over the parts that have walls.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Your favorite radio host Howard Stern said, doesn't work.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Where did you hear that?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: From you.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: There you go.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: At least we know Juan's listening.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. Only wants to hear what he wants. Major cracks in the BuzzFeed so-called bombshell story about President Trump and Michael Cohen, up next.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: President Trump's legal team is blasting a new BuzzFeed report claiming he instructed former personal lawyer, Michael Cohen, to lie to Congress about a potential real estate deal in Moscow. Rudy Giuliani is calling the report, quote, "categorically false," and is attacking Cohen as a convicted criminal and liar. The White House is pushing back on the use of unanimous sources. And there's a new controversy on whether the two reporters behind the story has seen corroborating evidence. Here's what one of them is saying.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Have you seen any of that other corroborating evidence?

utterances.speaker: ANTHONY CORMIER, BUZZFEED NEWS INVESTIGATIVE REPORTER
utterances.utterance: No, I've not seen it personally, but the folks that we've talked to -- the two officials that we've spoken to are fully 100 percent red end (ph) to that aspect of the special counsel investigation. They had access to a number of different documents, at that 302 (ph) reports which are interview reports.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Juan, you're the journalist here at the table.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Wait, excuse me. What? Well, I guess I didn't edit three magazines. Sorry.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And I guess I didn't --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, you guys -- I was about to set Juan up for failure, you like you ruined it for me.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I was only nominated for a national magazine award.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Such a life I had.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I could pretend to be a journalist too. What was I going to say? Oh, would you have gone with these two sources for a story -- there two sources that he says are red end (ph) but without seeing other evidence? Would you have taken those two editors --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, sure. The -- yeah. The question is whether or not they're independent of each other. You don't want two guys who are buddies --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And that we don't know.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: We thought we don't know. But, yes, you don't need to see. And if you've got two intelligence -- or in this case, law enforcement officials who say, oh, yeah, this is something that we know to be true, to be factual, and we've seen the documents. That's corroborating evidence. I think the bigger issue here is, I think, there're questions about some previous story done by one of these reporters in particular questions about whether or not he had told --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, that was actually -- I've dealt with that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I was an actual spokesperson one time. But this was a story about -- so Karl Rove in 2005 or 2006. Jason Leopold is one of these authors. He worked for a group called truthout.org and he picked up the story that said Karl had a tearful moment in the Oval Office where he informed the president and his White House colleagues that he was about to be indicted and goes to say -- none of that was true. And so, I was just reminded of that today. No other news outlet has matched this story. So these two officials if they exist, and I'm not saying that they don't, they might, but they're not talking to any other reporters.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah. And both reporters have different stories. Leopold said he has seen it, the other guy, Cormier, say he hasn't, anonymous sources. It's one of those what if stories. The business model these days for a lot of -- for BuzzFeed, MSNBC, CNN, it's Fred Sanford from Sanford and Son. Every week, he was certain he was going to have a massive heart attack. He would grab his heart. I'm coming. That's every Sanford and Son episode. And then he'd be there next week because -- people would forget about it. But this is actually the business model now because you're making money, you're getting viewers because you getting the audience riled up. And I don't know if they want what they want because the impeachment idea is lose-lose for the left and win-win for the right because it turns Trump into a folk hero, bigger than Paul Bunion (ph), and he ain't going away. You impeach him, he's just bigger than the president --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Not that they can take away --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And then you've got Mike Pence. It's going to be really hard to get him out. So my advice is go for the impeachment because it will be hilarious, or don't go for the impeachment and try to have an election in two years. We're already half way through. Why don't you try to beat the guy instead of trying to cheat the guy. Thank you.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And you know what the other thing about all of this, with the business model, is I really wish others would stop doing -- when these stories break at 10 PM --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What if true?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- big if true. Don't ever tweet that. Make it true.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: This is big if it's true. I'm going to put that out there. And Dana, my sources are saying this is fake news.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, OK.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: But I haven't seen any evidence from the sources. You can't see them either.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Listen, this guy, Leopold, has had a rough history. Salon removed a story by him, engaged in a lot of plagiarism, riddled with inaccuracy, and that's Salon. Now Salon has standards and it was too bad for them. That's a problem. He's also, in his personal life, he said he's engaged in lying, cheating, and back stabbing, and he has battled mental issue and struggled with substance abuse. I'm not saying that's coloring his reporting but take it with a grain of salt. That's all I'm saying. But, if -- this is big if it's true. Also, BuzzFeed was the same place that put out the dossier. And this is another one of those stories that there's just no corroboration, so how are we supposed to know?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: They were sued -- BuzzFeed was sued for that dossier, but they've actually won their lawsuit. Dr. Saphier, what do you think?

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: So, it's more anecdotal evidence as you say. And it is big if it's true. But it's only big if there's evidentiary or documentary truth. You can't just base all these off as total evidence because it's he said, she said. We saw the weight of this has played out before and it's not going to work. And unless the Mueller investigation is going to produces the blue dress we can't just base everything on a he said, she said. We really need some more documentary evidence.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Can I just pick up on this and say that -- so the way the things play out also offer clues. So, Lanny Davis who was Michael Cohen's lawyer was asked about this, and his response was, you know, we really can't talk. He didn't say no. And remember, previously they said no to some stories. This one, they didn't say that. And what you get here is a situation where people are now, you know, saying, well, we're not sure.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It doesn't matter, right? It doesn't matter. Juan, to your point, it doesn't matter if the story is true or not because it was originally about collusion and it's not even about that anymore. So now it's just -- if we can get one thing to stick and -- no, that's all it is.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think that's -- I think that's trying to deny --

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: Whitewater led to impeachment because he ended up lying. It wasn't necessarily has found of guilty of whitewater. And that's what they're trying to do here. OK, collusion is kind of out, so now they're just trying to get him into lying --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's what I'm saying, it doesn't matter.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. And the second point I wanted to make about the repercussions after we've heard this if true story was President Trump himself putting out this thing about, oh, I've got check for damaging information on Cohen's family.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan, this is a lying, embezzling rat being represented by a Clinton attorney --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You're talking about Michael Cohen.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Lanny Davis and Michael Cohen. Those two guys --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, my God.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Those two guys. OK. The women's march losing more key supporters, and its co-founder makes another controversy comment. It's a big one. That's ahead.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Welcome back. The women's march losing more support over antisemitism concerns ahead of this weekend big march in Washington, D.C. Florida's first Jewish congressman, Debbie Wasserman Schultz, writing an op-ed criticizing the group's leaders for tied to Nation of Islam leader, Louise Farrakhan. The former DNC chair also saying she will not be attending the Washington march. And after refusing to condemn Farrakhan earlier this week, women's march co-founder, Tamika Mallory, causing more controversy with these remarks.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Is it your view that Israel has a right to exist as a nation?

utterances.speaker: TAMIKA MALLORY, WOMEN MARCH CO-FOUNDER
utterances.utterance: I've said many times that I feel everyone has a right to exist. I feel everyone has a right to exist. I just don't feel that anyone has a right to exist at the disposal of another group.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: In your view, does that include Israeli and Israel?

utterances.speaker: MALLORY
utterances.utterance: I believe that all people have the right to exist.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Nicole, how do you understand what's going on?

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: She said I agree everyone has the right to exist just not at the disposal of other people. But Farrakhan actually said Hitler is a great man. And to my understanding, I think he disposed of a lot of people. So, I think this is terrible that this woman is not condemning his remarks. And it's not just anti-Semitism, he says white folks are going down. He attacks the LGBTQ community. So it's amazing to me that people can actually stand behind her if she can't condemn this man? I mean, talk about being divisive and people blaming President Trump and his administration, but when you have 3 to 5 million people following this women's march and the leaders won't condemn Farrakhan and his horrible views, that is where the division is coming from.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Jesse, in fact, there's lots of now local marches. I just read today the New Jersey group which is tied to Black Lives Matter is upset with the national march, but their local march is going forward again. This is all based on the 2017 march which turned out millions of people in Washington to oppose President Trump.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. My mother marched in the first women's march. So when I see her this weekend I'm going to say, mom, you better condemn. I don't want to see you matching with these radicals. And we'll see what she says. It's like the sister test but this is the mom test. Greg and a lot of other conservatives from pretty much a year have been highlighting the anti-Semitism of the people that had been leading this march.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I have.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So it took one year for the Democrats to actually hear what people had been saying. I guess that's how long it takes. I don't want to condemn the entire women's march because like the president I cherish women. But the leadership sticks from the head, OK? This was hijacked by radicals. And now, people are distancing themselves. And I don't see why it's so hard for the Democratic Party to distance themselves from Farrakhan. Farrakhan, live you've said praised Hitler, and has called Jews termites. And you have Barack Obama who had a photograph with him. Maxine Waters palling around with him, Keith Ellison, and now new members of congress praising him. Why is it so hard to distance yourself from Louis Farrakhan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think I have a picture with Louis Farrakhan.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, Williams. Condemn. Condemn.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You have to just say --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Can I use that excuse?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What I'm just saying this is -- I don't understand. But it sounds like you're on to something.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think so. I don't know what though.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Dana, today, there was a pro-life march in Washington, D.C.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: President Trump and Vice President Pence both had messages. What about that one?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, that march -- I had the director -- the president of March for Life, Jeanne Mancini, was on The Daily Briefing. And I've asked her how is it possible that you continue to have this march every year in the coldest weekend of the year and it grows every year. And you have younger people joining every year. And their theme this year really is about the science, and science being what is -- basically, changing people's minds. Change heart, you change minds, however it's happening. They're actually quite united. They're focused. They do not march for themselves. They march for people that are not able to march for themselves because they're not here. But when it comes to the women's march where there's division on the Democratic side --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. Can I interrupt for a second --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- and just say, though, I read there where there were divisions between people who said, "Well, I'm pro-life, but I'm not pro-Trump." And then people saying, "Well, should I go to this march or shouldn't I?"

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, the March for Life president said that they welcomed everybody. And because it was about - it wasn't not about a party or a certain person. It was about the issue of life. What I wanted to say about the other party is that -- or the other march is that there was no greater symbol of the resistance. Remember, it dominated news coverage for days, and it lasted so long that it propelled many Democratic women to wins in 2018. But now you have Debbie Wasserman Schultz, who's basically exacting revenge on her party with an op-ed in USA Today. This is not a -- they had the debate behind closed doors for a while, and now, it is all out in the open. They will never be able to create again or recreate that momentum that they had from the beginning. So they're -- they basically allowed this to stunt their growth. And it won't help them in 2020.

utterances.speaker: NICOLE SAPHIER, HOST
utterances.utterance: Well, you know what's interesting? Nancy Pelosi spoke at the last Women's March, and she said this year she couldn't go, likely, because she was supposed to be out of the country. But now she's going to be in the country, which we all know. So will she be attending the march? And if not, will she have to issue a statement as to why not?

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, HOST
utterances.utterance: Ooh.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So Greg, do you have high heels? Are you going tomorrow?

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, HOST
utterances.utterance: That's an interesting question. Do you need high heels to go to a woman's march?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't know. I don't know.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That seems kind of sexist to me.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: How insulting, sexist.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I do think Democrats --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, he wears flats.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. The Democrats deserve some recognition for stepping away from a hateful group of people that are a part of this organization. And we haven't even mentioned Linda Sarsour and Angela Davis. These are people that embraced terrorists and cop killers. But why did it take so long? That's what you're asking: why did it take so long? Emily Jashinsky from The Federalist answers this question today. Because there was no scrutiny. There was no scrutiny of the Women's March leaders, because we're all on the same team.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The media and the Women's March all are in agreement. So we'll take your anti-Semites.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We'll take your haters, and we'll focus on policing the alt- right. Because they're the -- they're the enemy. But please don't look in our back yard. But we have people that deny the Holocaust. We have people that laugh at Jews being persecuted, people that make excuses for cop killers. That's OK, because that's on your side. But I'm glad that so many people now are finally turning away from it. But it is an example. You have two variables here. Whenever you want to have a study on media bias, you have to have two variables. You have the Women's March; you have the March for Life. OK? The Women's March received so much press, favorable press, that you didn't know about a lot of this stuff. Meanwhile, the March for Life. Stoic. Selfless. Does it every year. Represents people who have no voice. Truly, a civil rights matter, because they are there for people who cannot speak. Unborn children cannot speak. And they are there; they are mocked. They are seen as old-fashioned. They are told that what they represent isn't even life. That it's some kind of tumor. There are people that actually make fun of them and made jokes about -- about being pro-life. But yet they show up. They're polite. They clean up after themselves.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But yet, they are ignored by the media. That is a perfect example of media bias. That's all.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't think it's an example of media bias, because they get coverage every year. I don't know who's mocking them. And guess what? Most Americans --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Let me do a Google search for you.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- still prefer legal abortion in this country. But you don't seem to want to hear that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I don't want to hear it, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: We're turning back the clock for the anniversary of what was a hilarious political moment. We want you to stay for the "Flashback on Friday." That's next on "The Five."

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: All right. Well, it's "Flashback Friday" here on "The Five." Can you believe this classic political gaffe is turning 15?

utterances.speaker: HOWARD DEAN, FORMER DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: Not only are we going to New Hampshire, Tom Harkin, we're going to South Carolina and Oklahoma and Arizona and North Dakota and New Mexico. We're going to California, and Texas and New York. And we're going to South Dakota and Oregon and Washington and Michigan! And then we're going to Washington, D.C., to take back the White House. Yeah!

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: All right. Well, the Dean scream started with the former Vermont governor trying to rally his supporters after finishing third in the Iowa causes. But instead, that screech killed his campaign. I mean, to be honest, this is my first time seeing this.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: What?

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: I was in the thick of medical school when this happened. But watching this --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: We should show it again. Because that was your first time.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: Well, no.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Can we show --

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: Watching this is like FDR fireside, compared to Obama and Trump.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It seems quaint now, but at the time, it was a really big deal.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: Yes, I mean, I get it. He's definitely enthused. But again, I wasn't necessarily impressed. And when people say it was like a big deal, he'dalready lost Iowa. I mean, he was coming in 3rd. It's not like this scream heard around the world --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well --

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: -- really did anything to his campaign.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well --

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: What do you think, Greg?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- it did during (ph) New Hampshire.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The -- so the yell is 15 years old. I guess that means R. Kelly can hit on it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oooh! Nice one.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Looking back at this, it's kind of unfair how life is, when you think about this, that one thing back then still exists because we choose to bring it up. It's the anniversary curse. "Oh, it's the tenth anniversary since Britney Spears beat up a car." So these anniversary things are what news likes to do. So they'll pick something that you do that was embarrassing --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- and then they replay it as an anniversary, because it's easy and it's something to do. And it's unfair, because now, if something happens to you or me --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Correct.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: OK, there's a lot of stuff that happens. Right now, the news happens quickly. Maybe it wouldn't. But if something happens to us, it's going to be played once a year. It's "Remember when Jesse Watters woke up and walked outside without his pants on?" And then it will be --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. Glad (ph) you said that instead of the other thing.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But you know what I mean.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think the producers made the right call in doing this.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I totally agree with the programming. Could we see it one more time? Could we please see it again? I need to see it.

utterances.speaker: DEAN
utterances.utterance: Not only are we going to New Hampshire, Tom Harkin, we're going to South Carolina and Oklahoma and Arizona and North Dakota and New Mexico. We're going to California, and Texas and New York. And we're going to South Dakota and Oregon and Washington and Michigan! And then we're going to Washington, D.C., to take back the White House. Yeah!

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: Well, let me tell you, this would be great is this was the one time he saw it. But he actually just did this again at the 2016 DNC convention. I mean, this is what he does; it's what he's known for. He says he still gets people asking his autographs for it. So --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He's said worse things. Believe me.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: I mean, Juan, what do you think, the showboating? Do you like the showboating on campaign trails or not?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't mind. I think showboating is a normal part of politics. But you know, it's so interesting that you had that response, because at the time, it did damage his campaign. People saw him as out of control, looking like he was -- I think, you know, Drudge had it as a headline. People then -- and this picks up on something that we see so much of today. Social media amplified it in a way that we hadn't seen before with a political error. And I just think that Howard Dean, even now, he says he gets asked about it. He has to autograph copies and tapes. It's an unbelievable moment in his life. He says that he just didn't have national political experience, didn't understand that he was holding the mic right there. People in the audience didn't have that negative response. Instead, it was people who were watching.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: I agree. They said it was to do with the microphone. But they were calling him hotheaded even before this. So Jesse, do you think that, really, the scream is what killed his campaign or was it just more ammunition?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It definitely damaged his campaign. I remember being a producer here at FOX, and we played it quite a bit.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Did you really?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Quite a bit.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'm surprised by that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I know.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I thought you would have had some compassion and moved on quickly.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No, no. That looped for about a week. But you know, this was a third-place finish. Imagine what he'd done if he'd finished first. And this guy, remember, he was the first real --

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: He was Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- grassroots, small-donation, Internet-driven, young-person candidate to come out at that time. No one had really done that before Howard Dean did it.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: So a young AOC. Is that what we're saying?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Sure. If -- I don't know if that's an insult to Dean or her.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: Well, we're going to move on, because we're not going to get onto AOC. So up next, a flip phone blast from the past is making a comeback. The Motorola Razr, which was popular years before the iPhone, is reportedly returning as a revamped smart phone with a foldable screen. But the price tag may surprise you. The update mobile device is going to cost a cool 1,500 bucks. Wow. All right. Dana, how much did you pay for your cellphone?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, I have an iPhone 10, so you can look it up, everybody. I got the iPhone 10. But I know people like their flip phone. The reason it's so expensive is because it has the actual screen that you can touch, as well. So I think that's why they're --

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: What's the benefit of the flip phone versus just having it right now the way it is?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Because you like the thing that cocks down next to your mouth. That was how the old-school -- see what I'm doing, Greg? -- that's how the old-school phones worked. You had a mouthpiece. Now there's no mouthpiece. So you like that "click." And it sounds good, too.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: You think people just like to do --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And it has the antenna. You can pull up the little antenna.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: Why do you think, Juan? What's your reaction?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think it's stylish. And I think there's only going to be 200,000 of them made. And so it becomes a real point of social status, I think, in the future. Because I mean, it's not -- it's not better than an iPhone. It's not better than a Galaxy. It's just cooler than a Galaxy or an iPhone.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Greg's going to get a -- Jitterbug.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: Greg, you getting one? Does Juan need to get one?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, I think we should go to the tease, because "Fan Mail Friday" is up next.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: All right. Don't go anywhere. "Fan Mail Friday" is up next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oops.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's "Fan Mail Friday." These are their stories.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: (LAUGHING)

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Thank you. Somebody laughed at that.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: I got it. Loved "Law & Order."

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: All right. This is from Sherri Marr. Good question: "What 1960s/'70s band is still your favorite or do you have one?" Well, Jesse, this is a perfect opportunity to say what you've been playing all week.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, I have bene playing Black Sabbath.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. People thought it was me, but it's actually you.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I know. You know, I'm amazed by the Black Sabbath reaction. So next week we're doing a two for Tuesday. More Black Sabbath.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Nice.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Should we give them what they want?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think you should. You can never have enough Black Sabbath.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: More Black Sabbath.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Black, bloody Sabbath, I say. Bloody Black Sabbath.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'm going to go --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right, Dana?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'm going to go with the Oak Ridge Boys.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Really?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I like the Oak Ridge Boys.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, they are quite nice, aren't they?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And they're still going.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Good fellows. Really good fellows. All right. Juan, what's your --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, in fact, today I heard that Gladys Knight is going to do "The Star-Spangled Banner" at the Super Bowl.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Wow. That's fantastic.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Greg, Jesse --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Imagine if we were the Pips. Right? Wouldn't that be great?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, you are the Pips.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's Dana's opinion.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I have the Pips.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But I mean, I think they were great.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wouldn't it have been fun? Like imagine if you were Earth, Wind and Fire.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. They are great outfits.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You're right. You could dress up. You know?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Jackson 5.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: All right, Doc.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: All right. I'm going to have to go with the Marshall Tucker Band.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I like them.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: With a combined tie with Roy Orbison, maybe.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know, it's weird. The '60s and 70s bands are now in their 70s and 80s. They really are. I'm going to go with Cheap Trick. Cheap Trick is one of the most underrated bands of the '70s and '80s. Should be --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: They're getting their due here on "The Five."

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, they are. And they're getting up there, too. Frenchi Firecracker --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Again.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- sixth member. What does that mean? "If you were to work a dirty job, what would you pick? That's amazing. Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Hmmm, dirty job? I'd be Greg's assistant.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I would be Juan's fact checker.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: There you go. There you go.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes! Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'm going to have to go with something on the ranch, like maybe milking cows.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Is that really a dirty job?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Not as dirty as it could be.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Remember when I milked that goat?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes. That was dirty.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think it was a goat.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, my God.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: All I know is it was quite messy and it didn't press charges. Doc.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: I would -- I would have to say that, being a doctor, sometimes is --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, I bet (ph).

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: -- a dirty job --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: True.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: -- if you consider blood and other things to be dirty.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: But outside of medicine, maybe a dog washer. Like, washing dogs and brushing them.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Is that really dirty?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: If you don't like hair.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And none of us are, like, working -- working the dirty jobs.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Come on, Jesse, pick a real dirty job.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right, CNN. I'd work for CNN. Filthy animals over there. Fake news, everybody.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, my God.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know what job I saw on TV? Maybe it was on "Dirty Jobs." The guy that has to dive into the sewage treatment plant to unclog it. So you have -- you're diving into a massing swimming-pool -size, like acres of raw sewage. And you've got to dive in there, so you wear a suit. And you've got to swim in there, and you've got to clear the clog. I would do that because nothing is dirtier than that, except for working at CNN.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: There you go.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Why don't we get you to do that next week for a package?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Let's not do that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know what happened on that one?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I was reading about El Chapo's trial. And he had an escape route under the bathtub.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And it went into the sewers.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: The sewers.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's like, no one's -- no one ever thinks of the sewer.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Like, the sewer.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: How do you get out?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's where my mind is, almost constantly.

utterances.speaker: All right. One more question
utterances.utterance: "If aliens attacked your house, what would be your go-to weapon?" Doc.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Aliens?

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: If aliens attacking my --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Come on, you're a doctor.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: I don't know. Aliens? I don't -- I'm like --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Space aliens, mind you.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: My mom face.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: There you go.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: I can make a face.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That would work. Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I have a switch blade at home. Should I have not said that?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What is this, "Westside Story"? Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: My dad's Christmas present to me.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh!

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That we can't talk about.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Wow! Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: My wife. I'd send her after them. They would run away!

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, I would fling human waste at them. Because I -- because I don't -- unfortunately, in New York City, you can't have a gun. Or at least, I say that I can't have a gun. But that's what I would do.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You're in the sewer again.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But where would you get it?

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: You can just do that on demand?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: A special -- special talent that I -- I've learned. . "One More Thing" is up next.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Time for "One More Thing." Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Remember this scene from the movie "Jaws"?

utterances.speaker: ROY SCHEIDER, ACTOR
utterances.utterance: You're going to need a bigger boat.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, now take a look at this real-life monster of a shark. Yes, this 20-footer was seen Tuesday near Hawaii. A shark research team encountered the shark feasting on the carcass of a sperm whale. Luckily, for the researchers, the shark didn't eat them. By the way, the researchers think this is the largest known giant white shark, but they're not sure. They saw one this size before and called it Deep Blue. They suspect this one, possibly a pregnant female, could be just another humongous shark.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. Greg, thoughts on sharks?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We really don't need to show a "Jaws" clip when we're showing a giant shark. I mean, that just tore about 20, 25 seconds out of the show. I mean, come on. All right. "The Greg Gutfeld Show, 10 p.m. tomorrow night. It's going to be a doozy. Heather Zumarraga, Pete Hegseth, Kat Timpf, and Tyrus. That's 10 p.m. January 19. Saturday, Saturday, Saturday! All right. It's time for --

utterances.speaker: GRAPHIC
utterances.utterance: Greg's Cat-Off.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- "Greg's Cat-Off." You know the rules.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I love this.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We have three cat videos. We on the panel vote which one is the most cat-like. And you at home can vote by screaming your answer out a window at a stranger. Let's go to the first cat. All right. Here we've got a cat trying to say hello to its reflection. It doesn't know what's happening, because it's stupid. The second cat, let's go to the second cat. This cat, what is it doing? Here it is. Oh, it's petting water, because it thinks that maybe water goes through its paws. That's another stupid cat. All right. Now we go to the third cat. The final cat. The only cat that matters. Aww. A cat that enjoys the soft feel of a paint roller.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's an ugly cat.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It is not an ugly cat. That's a beautiful cat. All right. I think we've seen enough cats. Let's go to the votes. Doc, what's your vote for Cat-Off?

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: I mean, the super cute one is the little kitty. The first one.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The first one, No. 1. Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No. 1.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Whoa.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Numero uno.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Wow, three?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'm going with No. 3.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: There you go. And I am not going to be a tie-breaker, and I'm going to go with the No. 2. Therefore, No. 1 wins, 3-1-1.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Wow, that was exhausting.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It was. I'm tired.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: That wasn't a tiebreaker.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'm tired.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: Three to two.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: A catbreaker.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: That would have been three to two. Not a tiebreaker.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Time for -- "Jesse's Unsolved Mysteries." Some very strange happenings in the sky over Moscow. Massive smoke ring appearing, basically just hanging in the air. Is it a UFO? Is it a portal to another dimension? Are these smoke signals being sent from the Kremlin to the White House? No, Juan, they are not.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No. OK.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Maybe it's sending to Elizabeth Warren.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What is it?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: We don't know. It's an unsolved mystery, Greg. That's why we made that graphic. Also, "Watters' World," 8 p.m. Saturday night with Sarah Sanders, we think. We'll see what happens. Anything could happen.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right. So this weekend, NFL's top team -- you know there's football going on this weekend. I've got "Dana's Mascot Theory." Here we go. For the NFC championship, airing on FOX, we have Rampage the Ram taking on Sir Saint and Gumbo. So usually, I think I'd go with Rampage because you've the horns. But two mascots are better than just one. So I do think that --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What ugly mascots.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- they're going to win. So with the AFC, things get a little bit tricky, because you've got Pat the Patriot and you've got KC, the Wolf. And often you can go with Pat, because he's got a gun, but I think the wolf is quite wily. I'm going to go with the Chiefs on that one.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'd go with the --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No. The guy has a gun. The patriot.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. Nicole.

utterances.speaker: SAPHIER
utterances.utterance: Well, one Pennsylvania police department put out a call for a few good men -- who are willing to get drunk. That's right, guys. The Kutztown Police Department sought three volunteers to drink hard liquor to the point of inebriation. This was so officers could be trained on how to administer field sobriety tests during traffic stop. Needless to say, it's had over 1,000 shares, and they got enough volunteers. They got their three. And they're good to go, I guess.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Greg just signed up to be a police officer.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: In Kutztown. Kutztown.
